  "title": "Guido Baselgia",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cfacc05c8a6c1633",
      "text": "In his search for the last valid image, photographer Guido Baselgia paradoxically travels to places where there is hardly any light, for example to Tierra del Fuego or the northernmost point of Europe. The film accompanies him and shows how images are created that look behind the surface.\n\nThe photo artist Guido Baselgia, who grew up in Pontresina GR, is one of the most important photo artists in Switzerland. In elaborate research, he examines landscapes of extremes and travels to the ends of the earth to do so, for example to the southernmost tip of Tierra del Fuego, to the Amazon or to Norway at the northernmost point of Europe. With his large-format analog camera and under extreme weather conditions, he spends nights alone in places where there is hardly any light. In the process, he creates images that, precisely because of their utmost precision, tip over into abstraction, where it is no longer clear whether what is depicted is sand or snow, or whether it is a day or night image. His pictures show the archaic and untouched of the earth, penetrate deeply into nature and let us see it with new eyes."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cc1ac8223293fae5",
      "text": "Filmmaker [[Casper Nicca]] accompanied Baselgia on this quest for three years. The result is a quiet film portrait that is directly involved in Guido Baselgia's artistic work, which confronts him and us with the elemental force of nature."
